## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| 🔴 Critical | 2 (systemic — affects all 10 tests) |
| 🟠 High | 0 |
| 🟡 Medium | 2 |
| 🔵 Low | 1 |

**This test class is a textbook coverage-touching suite.** All 10 public methods of `ProductCatalog` are called, which produces impressive coverage metrics, but **zero business outcomes are verified**. Six tests have no assertions at all; the remaining four use only `Assert.IsNotNull`, which passes for any non-null value regardless of correctness.

---

### 🔴 Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (systemic — all 10 tests)

The entire class follows a methodical pattern: call every public method on `ProductCatalog`, in roughly declaration order, without verifying outcomes. This inflates code-coverage to ~95% while proving nothing about correctness.

**Tests with zero assertions (6/10):**

| Test Method | Line | What goes unverified |
|---|---|---|
| `AddProduct_Works` | 17 | Product was actually persisted |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` | 31 | Price was actually changed to 14.99 |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` | 39 | Product was actually deleted |
| `GetProductCount_Works` | 62 | Count value is correct |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` | 68 | Prices were reduced by 10% |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` | 84 | Any product was actually imported |

**Example — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 68):**

The production code could apply the discount backwards (`1 + fraction` instead of `1 - fraction`), doubling prices, and this test would still pass.

```csharp
// BEFORE — no assertion, always passes
[TestMethod]
public void ApplyBulkDiscount_Works()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-002", "Gadget", 19.99m));
    _catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
}

// AFTER — verifies the actual business outcome
[TestMethod]
public void ApplyBulkDiscount_ReducesPricesByFraction()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 10.00m));
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-002", "Gadget", 20.00m));

    _catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

    Assert.AreEqual(9.00m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
    Assert.AreEqual(18.00m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
}
```

**Example — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39):**

```csharp
// BEFORE — removal is never verified
[TestMethod]
public void RemoveProduct_Works()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
